  "text": "The ratios of lateral heights h a /h p and h m /h p (h m : middle lateral vertebral body height) were considered by Sone et al. [CITATION_1] as the parameters that allowed the assessment of mild vertebral fractures and the prediction of fracture susceptibility. They investigated T12-L4 vertebral height ratios of 479 pre-and postmenopausal Japanese females and the relationship of these ratios to age and aBMD. Height ratios, and especially h m /h p , tended to decrease with age and positively correlated with aBMD. The correlation coefficients were r = -0.125 (p \\ 0.05) for the dependence between h a /h p and age for L3 vertebrae, while r = -0.180 (p \\ 0.01) for the relationship between age and h m /h p . Statistical analysis showed no significant correlation between aBMD and h a /h p for L3 vertebrae, while r = 0.145 (p \\ 0.01) for the dependence between aBMD and h m /h p .",
